{"cursor":"21187","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Coulomb's law' or Coulomb's inverse-square law is a law of physics describing\nthe electrostatic interaction between electrically charged particles. It was\nfirst published in 1785 by French physicist Charles Augustin de Coulomb and was\nessential to the development of the theory of electromagnetism. This law states\nthat \"The force of attraction or repulsion between two point charges is directly\nproportional to the product of magnitude of each charge and inversely\nproportional to the square of distance between them\". In --\nCoulomb (1785a)\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=by5EAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA569#v=onepage&q&f=false\n\"Premier mÃ©moire sur lâÃ©lectricitÃ© et le magnÃ©tisme,\"] Histoire de lâAcadÃ©mie\nRoyale des Sciences, pages 569-577 -- Coulomb studied the repulsive force\nbetween bodies having electrical charges of the same sign: Page 574 : Il rÃ©sulte donc de ces trois essais, que l'action\nrÃ©pulsive que les deux balles Ã©lectrifÃ©es de la mÃªme nature d'Ã©lectricitÃ©\nexercent l'une sur l'autre, suit la raison inverse du carrÃ© des\ndistances. Translation : It follows therefore from these\nthree tests, that the repulsive force that the two balls -- [that were]\nelectrified with the same kind of electricity -- exert on each other, follows\nthe inverse proportion of the square of the distance. In -- Coulomb\n(1785b)\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=by5EAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA578#v=onepage&q&f=false\n\"Second mÃ©moire sur lâÃ©lectricitÃ© et le magnÃ©tisme,\"] Histoire de lâAcadÃ©mie\nRoyale des Sciences, pages 578-611. -- Coulomb showed that oppositely charged\nbodies obey an inverse-square law of attraction. Other\nearly investigators who suspected that the electrical force diminished with\ndistance as the gravitational force did (i.e., as the inverse square of the\ndistance) included Daniel Bernoulli (see: Abel Socin (1760) Acta HelvetiÑa, vol.\n4, pages [http://www.archive.org/stream/actahelveticaphy04helv#page/224/mode/2up\n224-225].) and Alessandro Volta, both of whom measured the force between plates\nof a capacitor, and Aepinus who supposed the inverse-square law in 1758. See:\nJ.L. Heilbron, Electricity in the 17th and 18th Centuries: A Study of Early\nModern Physics (Los Angeles, California: University of California Press, 1979),\npages 460-462, and\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=UlTLRUn1sy8C&pg=PA464#v=onepage&q&f=false 464]\n(including footnote 44). Coulomb's law has been tested heavily and all\nobservations are consistent with the law.\n","linknr":458,"url":"Coulomb's_law","recorded":1362485665,"links":82,"instances":["mathematics","physicist"],"pdf":["http://www.physnet.org/modules/pdf_modules/m114.pdf"],"categories":["Electrostatics","Concepts in physics","Article Feedback 5 Additional Articles"],"headings":["History","The law","Scalar form","Vector form","Electrostatic approximation","Table of derived quantities (relevant for vacuum only)","See also","Notes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/VFPt_Solenoid_correct2.svg/190px-VFPt_Solenoid_correct2.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/42/Coulomb.jpg/100px-Coulomb.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Bcoulomb.png/100px-Bcoulomb.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/73/Coulombslaw.svg/392px-Coulombslaw.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/f/6/3f67479eda67aa1df0b2b44ca10a116d.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/3/c/43cfd29869833e7377d49cc8b89c101c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ea/Electric_field_one_charge_changing.gif/220px-Electric_field_one_charge_changing.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/e/f/6ef8759138292